been enforced. Drawing on ethnographic fieldwork and in-depth interview data, she finds that contradictory policies at the national, state, and local levels interact to create a complex environment through which the youth must navigate. From heritage-based school programs to state-wide bans on attending community college; from the failure of the DREAM Act to the rescinding of Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA); each layer represents profound implications for undocumented Latino youth. Silver exposes the constantly changing pathways that shape their journeys into early adulthood-and the profound resilience that they develop along the way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aChildren of immigrantszNorth Carolina. 0aHispanic American youthzNorth Carolina. 0aIllegal alienszNorth Carolina. 0aImmigrant youthzNorth Carolina. 0aLatin AmericanszNorth Carolina. 4a1.5-generation. 4aDACA. 4aImmigrant Incorporation. 4aImmigrant Youth. 4aNew Destination. 4aNew Latino South. 4aUnauthorized Immigration. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360575640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605756423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605756.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles